In .NET MAUI, you use the **lifecycle events mapper** in `MauiProgram.cs` via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;

public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>()
        .ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
        {
#if ANDROID
            events.AddAndroid(android => android
                .OnPause(activity =>
                {
                    // runs on Android OnPause
                })
                .OnStop(activity =>
                {
                    // runs on Android OnStop
                }));
#elif IOS
            events.AddiOS(ios => ios
                .DidEnterBackground(app =>
                {
                    // runs on iOS DidEnterBackground
                }));
#endif
        });

    return builder.Build();
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`ConfigureLifecycleEvents`** is the single entry point for all platform lifecycle hooks.
- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#elif IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code compiled only for the target.
- `AddAndroid(...)` exposes the full `Activity` lifecycle (`OnCreate`, `OnResume`, `OnPause`, `OnStop`, `OnDestroy`, etc.).
- `AddiOS(...)` exposes `UIApplicationDelegate` events (`WillFinishLaunching`, `DidEnterBackground`, `WillEnterForeground`, etc.).
- The delegate parameter gives you the native object (`Activity` on Android, `UIApplication` on iOS) so you can call platform APIs directly.
